article.headline: San Francisco 98, San Diego 88
article.story: SAN DIEGO (AP) -- Antonio Kellogg scored 21 points and San Francisco used a stifling defense to defeat San Diego 98-88 on Saturday. The Dons' suffocating half-court zone press helped them to take a commanding 56-30 halftime lead. San Francisco had nine steals and pressured the Toreros into 15 first-half turnovers that led to numerous easy baskets. The Dons won the rematch of last month's game at San Francisco when they beat San Diego 103-100 in double overtime. San Francisco (9-14, 5-3 West Coast), which shot 66.7 percent (20-for-30) from the field in the first half, made 14 of its first 18 shots as it took a 36-11 lead with 8:37 to go in the half. Kellogg made 6-of-8 shots and was 8-for-9 from the free throw line as the Dons finished shooting 59.3 percent from the field. Armando Surratt and Manny Quezada added 17 points apiece, Johnny Dukes had 14 and Alan Wiggins Jr. scored 13 points. The biggest deficit facing San Diego (13-10, 3-5 West Coast) was when it trailed 64-32 with just more than 17 minutes left in the game. The Toreros went on a 27-10 run that cut the lead to 74-59 with just less than nine minutes left. But San Diego could only get as close as 14 points later in the half before both teams subbed out their starters in the final minute. Gyno Pomare led the Toreros with 18 points and Ross DeRogatis added 17.
